  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 41.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he gave them into the hand of the heathen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This is the great lesson taught by Jewish history, and especially impressed upon us by Judges and Chronicles. When a nation sins, it is delivered over to its enemies, partly for punishment, partly to lead it to repentance. Israel was delivered into the hand, first, of Mesopotamia (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), then of Moab (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), next of the Philistines (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), then of the Canaanites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 4:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), later on of Midian (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), still later of Ammon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 10:7-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and then of the Philistines once more (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 13:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") - on each occasion because of some flagrant sins, and suffered chastisement until it repented. So we are told in Chronicles with respect to the invasions of Shishak (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:2-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), of Pul (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 5:25, 26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), of Tiglath-pileser (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 28:19, 20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and of Nebuchadnezzar (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 36:13-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), that they were on account of the people's transgressions. God \"slew\" them that they might \"seek him,\" and the ordinary result was, that they \"turned themselves, and inquired after God.\" And they that hated them ruled over them. Chushan-rishathaim for eight years (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Eglon for eighteen (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Jabin for twenty (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 4:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the Midianites for seven (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the Ammonites for eighteen (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 10:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the Philistines for forty (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 13:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Psalm 106:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The sins in Canaan: the failing to exterminate the idolatrous peoples and sharing in their idolatry. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 106:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the poet appeals to the command, frequently enjoined upon them from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 23:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". onwards, to extirpate the inhabitants of Canaan. Since they did not execute this command (vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), that which it was intended to prevent came to pass: the heathen became to them a snare (mowqeesh), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 23:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 34:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". They intermarried with them, and fell into the Canaanitish custom in which the abominations of heathenism culminate, viz., the human sacrifice, which Jahve abhorreth (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 12:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and only the demons (שׁדים, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") delight in. Thus then the land was defiled by blood-guiltiness (חנף, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 35:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 24:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 26:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and they themselves became unclean (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 20:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") by the whoredom of idolatry. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 106:40-43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the poet (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 9:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) sketches the alternation of apostasy, captivity, redemption, and relapse which followed upon the possession of Canaan, and more especially that which characterized the period of the judges. God's \"counsel\" was to make Israel free and glorious, but they leaned upon themselves, following their own intentions (בּעצתם); wherefore they perished in their sins. The poet uses מכך (to sink down, fall away) instead of the נמק (to moulder, rot) of the primary passage, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", retained in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 24:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 33:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which is no blunder (Hitzig), but a deliberate change. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]